Ggplot2

Task 1

Create a simple scatterplot using ggplot2 where x axis shows EngineSize, y axis shows MPG.city.

  • Use blue color for your dots.
  • Use size = 2 for the dot sizes.
  • Use xlim and ylim to make sure your x and y axis ranges make sense.
  • Add a title, subtitle, x axis label, y axis label, and a caption using title, subtitle, caption options inside + labs().
library(MASS)
data(Cars93)
library(ggplot2)
scatterPlot <- ggplot(data= Cars93, aes(x=EngineSize, y=MPG.city)) + geom_point(color="blue", size=2) + xlim(0,10)+ylim(0,50)+ labs(title="Scatterplot of Engine Size and MPG City", subtitle="Comparing between car models", x='Engine Size', y="MPG City", caption='Cars93 Dataset')
print(scatterPlot)

Task 2

Recreate the scatterplot in Task 1. Add the following functionality:

  • Use a different color for each car Type.
library(MASS)
data(Cars93)
library(ggplot2)
scatterPlot <- ggplot(data= Cars93, aes(x=EngineSize, y=MPG.city, color=Type)) + geom_point( size=2) + xlim(0,10)+ylim(0,50)+ labs(title="Scatterplot of Engine Size and MPG City", subtitle="Comparing between car models", x='Engine Size', y="MPG City", caption='Cars93 Dataset')

print(scatterPlot)

Task 3

Recreate the scatterplot in Task 2. Add the following functionality:

  • Fit and overlay a smooth curve.
  • Make the curve line red, and dashed. (Hint linetype is the option you can use to set line style as dashed)
library(MASS)
data(Cars93)
library(ggplot2)

scatterPlot <- ggplot(data = Cars93, aes(x = EngineSize, y = MPG.city, color = Type)) + 
  geom_point(size = 2) + xlim(0, 10) +  ylim(0, 50) + 
  labs( title = "Scatterplot of Engine Size and MPG City",subtitle = "Comparing between car models", x = 'Engine Size',  y = "MPG City", caption = 'Cars93 Dataset') + geom_smooth(meth9od="loess", color="red", linetype="dashed")

Task 4

Create a barplot showing count of cars by AirBags using ggplot2.

  • geom_bar() is the function that creates a barplot.
  • Use a different color for each bar.
  • Add a title, subtitle, x axis label, y axis label, and a caption using title, subtitle, caption options inside + labs().
library(MASS)
data(Cars93)
library(ggplot2)
barPlot <- ggplot(data=Cars93, aes(x=AirBags, fill= AirBags))+ geom_bar()+labs(title="Count of cars by Airbags", subtitle="Airbag types in Cars", x="AirBags", y="Count", caption="Cars93 Dataset")
print(barPlot)

Task 5

Recreate the barplot in Task 4 for different car Origin, such that you create one barplot for each Origin category and display all on the same graph.

  • You can have Origin as the x variable by setting x=Origin.
  • Use fill=AirBags to get a different color (and bar) by AirBags.
  • in geom_bar(), useposition=dodge` to have the barplots side by side.
library(MASS)
data(Cars93)
library(ggplot2)
barPlot <- ggplot(data=Cars93, aes(x=Origin, fill= AirBags)) + geom_bar(position = 'dodge')+ labs(title="Count of Cars by Airbags for each origin", subtitle="Fistribution of Airbag types", x='origin', y='count', caption='Cars93 Dataset')+facet_wrap(~Origin, scales = "free_x")
print(barPlot)

Task 1

Create a map of Australia using ggplot2.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot()+geom_sf(data= au_states)+ labs(title= "Map of Australia")

Task 4

Lets take a look at a different projection output. Change your maps projection to epsg 3112 by adding + coord_sf(). Recall the option that goes inside coord_sf() is st_crs(4_digit_code)

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
ausMap <- ggplot()+ 
  geom_sf(data=au_states, aes(fill=NAME))+
  labs(title="Map Of Australia")+
  coord_sf(crs=st_crs(3112))
print(ausMap)

Lets display the capitals on the map like before. First convert the au_capitals dataframe to spatial dataframe object by running:

capitals_geo <- st_as_sf(au_capitals, coords = c("lon", "lat"))
